This paper explores the diversity of knowledge representations across different language editions of Wikipedia, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP) and information retrieval (IR). Therefore, cs.CL and cs.IR are the most likely sub-categories. Additionally, the study also touches upon the cultural and linguistic aspects of user-generated content, which could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.CY (computational social science) and cs.SI (social and information networks). Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of leveraging knowledge diversity, which could fall under the sub-category of cs.DL (machine learning).
